[src:robyn-python/event-loop] In software, an **event loop** is an algorithm that continually dispatches control flow for events.
[src:robyn-python/event-loop] The loop requests the next event from an event provider (which generally blocks the loop until an event occurs), and when an event is received, invokes its associated event handler.
[src:robyn-python/event-loop] When the event loop is the central event dispatcher of a program, as it often is, it is called the **main loop** or **main event loop**.
[src:robyn-python/event-loop] In modern environments such as web browsers and server runtimes, the event loop is a fundamental mechanism that enables asynchronous execution by continuously monitoring and dispatching events or messages from a queue when the main program thread is idle.
[src:robyn-python/event-loop] In JavaScript, the event loop allows non-blocking handling of tasks such as user interactions, timers, and I/O operations despite the language being single-threaded.
[src:robyn-python/event-loop] The same algorithm can be used to process inbound messages, a superset of events.
[src:robyn-python/event-loop] In this context, the algorithm is called a **message loop**, **message dispatcher**, or **message pump**.
[src:robyn-python/event-loop] A common use for a message loop is message passing inter-process communication where the message queue is maintained outside of the program (such as by the operating system).
[src:robyn-python/event-loop] Typically, a program that operates in a graphical user interface (GUI) environment uses an event loop, and due to the predominance of GUI environments, most modern applications have a main event loop.
[src:robyn-python/event-loop] In the following pseudocode, `get_next_message()` is a placeholder for a function that is typically provided by the operating system that blocks until a message is available.
[src:robyn-python/event-loop] Thus, the loop only repeats when there is a message to process.
[src:robyn-python/event-loop] Many programs include an event loop in the high-level design; a main event loop, but there are alternative designs.
[src:robyn-python/event-loop] A program can exit as soon as it completes the actions that it's designed to do without external (i.e. user) interaction.
[src:robyn-python/event-loop] Often, such a program has optional behavior that is set up before the program starts such as via the command-line interface (CLI) or environment variables.
[src:robyn-python/event-loop] Utility software is often of this nature.
[src:robyn-python/event-loop] Even if a program provides for user interaction, it might not use an event loop.
[src:robyn-python/event-loop] A program that provides an internal CLI does include a command processor that is similar to an event loop in that it dispatches to command handlers based on user input.
[src:robyn-python/event-loop] A web page and its JavaScript typically run in a single-threaded web browser process.
[src:robyn-python/event-loop] The browser process deals with messages from a queue one at a time.
[src:robyn-python/event-loop] A JavaScript function or another browser event might be associated with a given message.
[src:robyn-python/event-loop] When the browser process has finished with a message, it proceeds to the next message in the queue.
[src:robyn-python/event-loop] In JavaScript environments, the event loop works with separate queues — including a task queue and a microtask queue — to manage asynchronous operations such as timers, promise callbacks, and DOM events.
[src:robyn-python/event-loop] When the call stack is empty, the event loop selects the next task from these queues to execute.
[src:robyn-python/event-loop] In Windows, a process that interacts with the user must accept and react to incoming messages, which is almost inevitably done by a message loop in that process.
[src:robyn-python/event-loop] In Windows, a message is equated to an event created and imposed upon the operating system.
[src:robyn-python/event-loop] An event can be user interaction, network traffic, system processing, timer activity, inter-process communication, among others.
[src:robyn-python/event-loop] For non-interactive, I/O only events, Windows has I/O completion ports.
[src:robyn-python/event-loop] I/O completion port loops run separately from the Message loop, and do not interact with the Message loop out of the box.
[src:robyn-python/event-loop] The heart of most Win32 applications is the WinMain() function, which calls GetMessage() in a loop.
[src:robyn-python/event-loop] GetMessage() blocks until a message (event), is received (with function PeekMessage() as a non-blocking alternative).
[src:robyn-python/event-loop] After some optional processing, it will call DispatchMessage(), which dispatches the message to the relevant handler, also known as WindowProc.
[src:robyn-python/event-loop] Normally, messages that have no special WindowProc() are dispatched to DefWindowProc, the default one.
[src:robyn-python/event-loop] DispatchMessage() calls the WindowProc of the HWND handle of the message (registered with the RegisterClass() function).
[src:robyn-python/event-loop] More recent versions of Windows guarantee that messages will be delivered to an application's message loop in the order that they were perceived by the system and its peripherals.
[src:robyn-python/event-loop] This guarantee is essential when considering the design consequences of multithreaded applications.
[src:robyn-python/event-loop] However, some messages have different rules, such as messages that are always received last, or messages with a different documented priority.
[src:robyn-python/event-loop] X applications using Xlib directly are built around the `XNextEvent` family of functions; `XNextEvent` blocks until an event appears on the event queue, whereupon the application processes it appropriately.
[src:robyn-python/event-loop] The Xlib event loop only handles window system events; applications that need to be able to wait on other files and devices could construct their own event loop from primitives such as `ConnectionNumber`, but in practice tend to use multithreading.
[src:robyn-python/event-loop] In the more common case, GUI toolkits based on Xlib usually support adding events.
[src:robyn-python/event-loop] For example, toolkits based on Xt Intrinsics have `XtAppAddInput()` and `XtAppAddTimeout()`.
[src:robyn-python/event-loop] It is not safe to call Xlib functions from a signal handler, because the X application may have been interrupted in an arbitrary state, e.g. within `XNextEvent`.
[src:robyn-python/event-loop] See [1] for a solution for X11R5, X11R6 and Xt.
[src:robyn-python/event-loop] The GLib event loop was originally created for use in GTK but is now used in non-GUI applications as well, such as D-Bus.
[src:robyn-python/event-loop] The resource polled is the collection of file descriptors the application is interested in; the polling block will be interrupted if a signal arrives or a timeout expires (e.g. if the application has specified a timeout or idle task).
[src:robyn-python/event-loop] Application libraries that are built on the GLib event loop include GStreamer and the asynchronous I/O methods of GnomeVFS, but GTK remains the most visible client library.
[src:robyn-python/event-loop] Events from the windowing system (in X, read off the X socket) are translated by GDK into GTK events and emitted as GLib signals on the application's widget objects.
[src:robyn-python/event-loop] Exactly one CFRunLoop is allowed per thread, and arbitrarily many sources and observers can be attached.
[src:robyn-python/event-loop] Sources then communicate with observers through the run loop, with it organising queueing and dispatch of messages.
[src:robyn-python/event-loop] The CFRunLoop is abstracted in Cocoa as an NSRunLoop, which allows any message (equivalent to a function call in non-reflective runtimes) to be queued for dispatch to any object.
[src:robyn-python/event-loop] In Unix, the everything is a file paradigm leads to a file-based event loop.
[src:robyn-python/event-loop] Reading from and writing to files, inter-process communication, network communication, and device control are all achieved using file I/O, with the target identified by a file descriptor.
[src:robyn-python/event-loop] The select and poll system calls allow a set of file descriptors to be monitored for a change of state, e.g. when data becomes available to be read.
[src:robyn-python/event-loop] In Unix, a signal is an asynchronous event that is handled by a signal handler which runs while the rest of the task is suspended.
[src:robyn-python/event-loop] If a signal is received and handled while the task is blocking in `select()`, select will return early with EINTR; if a signal is received while the task is CPU bound, the task will be suspended between instructions until the signal handler returns.
[src:robyn-python/event-loop] A way to handle a signal is for signal handlers to set a global flag and have the event loop check for the flag immediately before and after the `select()` call; if it is set, handle the signal in the same manner as with events on file descriptors.
[src:robyn-python/event-loop] Unfortunately, this gives rise to a race condition: if a signal arrives immediately between checking the flag and calling `select()`, it will not be handled until `select()` returns for some other reason (for example, being interrupted by a frustrated user).
[src:robyn-python/event-loop] The solution arrived at by POSIX is the `pselect()` call, which is similar to `select()` but takes an additional `sigmask` parameter, which describes a *signal mask*.
[src:robyn-python/event-loop] This allows an application to mask signals in the main task, then remove the mask for the duration of the `select()` call such that signal handlers are only called while the application is I/O bound.
[src:robyn-python/event-loop] However, implementations of `pselect()` have not always been reliable; versions of Linux prior to 2.6.16 do not have a `pselect()` system call, forcing glibc to emulate it via a method prone to the very same race condition `pselect()` is intended to avoid.
[src:robyn-python/event-loop] An alternative, more portable solution, is to convert asynchronous events to file-based events using the *self-pipe trick*, where "a signal handler writes a byte to a pipe whose other end is monitored by `select()` in the main program".
[src:robyn-python/event-loop] In Linux kernel version 2.6.22, a new system call `signalfd()` was added, which allows receiving signals via a special file descriptor.
[src:robyn-python/event-loop] In environments such as web browsers and Node.js, the event loop is central to asynchronous program behavior.
[src:robyn-python/event-loop] JavaScript runs on a single thread for execution, but host environments provide APIs for non-blocking operations, such as timers, network requests, and user events.
[src:robyn-python/event-loop] Completed asynchronous operations are placed in queues, and the event loop repeatedly checks whether the call stack is empty to schedule queued callbacks.
[src:robyn-python/event-loop] This enables JavaScript applications to remain responsive while handling multiple asynchronous tasks.
[src:robyn-python/multi-core-processor] A **multi-core processor** (**MCP**) is a microprocessor on a single integrated circuit (IC) with two or more separate central processing units (CPUs), called *cores* to emphasize their multiplicity (for example, *dual-core* or *quad-core*).
[src:robyn-python/multi-core-processor] Each core reads and executes program instructions, specifically ordinary CPU instructions (such as add, move data, and branch).
[src:robyn-python/multi-core-processor] However, the MCP can run instructions on separate cores at the same time, increasing overall speed for programs that support multithreading or other parallel computing techniques.
[src:robyn-python/multi-core-processor] Manufacturers typically integrate the cores onto a single IC die, known as a **chip multiprocessor** (**CMP**), or onto multiple dies in a single chip package.
[src:robyn-python/multi-core-processor] As of 2024, the microprocessors used in almost all new personal computers are multi-core.
[src:robyn-python/multi-core-processor] A multi-core processor implements multiprocessing in a single physical package.
[src:robyn-python/multi-core-processor] Designers may couple cores in a multi-core device tightly or loosely.
[src:robyn-python/multi-core-processor] For example, cores may or may not share caches, and they may implement message passing or shared-memory inter-core communication methods.
[src:robyn-python/multi-core-processor] Common network topologies used to interconnect cores include bus, ring, two-dimensional mesh, and crossbar.
[src:robyn-python/multi-core-processor] Just as with single-processor systems, cores in multi-core systems may implement architectures such as VLIW, superscalar, vector, or multithreading.
[src:robyn-python/multi-core-processor] Multi-core processors are widely used across many application domains, including general-purpose, embedded, network, digital signal processing (DSP), and graphics (GPU).
[src:robyn-python/multi-core-processor] Core count goes up to even dozens, and for specialized chips over 10,000, and in supercomputers (i.e. clusters of chips) the count can go over 10 million (and in one case up to 20 million processing elements total in addition to host processors).
[src:robyn-python/multi-core-processor] The improvement in performance gained by the use of a multi-core processor depends very much on the software algorithms used and their implementation.
[src:robyn-python/multi-core-processor] In particular, possible gains are limited by the fraction of the software that can run in parallel simultaneously on multiple cores; this effect is described by Amdahl's law.
[src:robyn-python/multi-core-processor] In the best case, so-called embarrassingly parallel problems may realize speedup factors near the number of cores, or even more if the problem is split up enough to fit within each core's cache(s), avoiding use of much slower main-system memory.
[src:robyn-python/multi-core-processor] Most applications, however, are not accelerated as much unless programmers invest effort in refactoring.
[src:robyn-python/multi-core-processor] The parallelization of software is a significant ongoing topic of research.
[src:robyn-python/multi-core-processor] Cointegration of multiprocessor applications provides flexibility in network architecture design.
[src:robyn-python/multi-core-processor] Adaptability within parallel models is an additional feature of systems utilizing these protocols.
[src:robyn-python/multi-core-processor] In the consumer market, dual-core processors (that is, microprocessors with two units) started becoming commonplace on personal computers in the late 2000s.
[src:robyn-python/multi-core-processor] In the early 2010s, quad-core processors were also being adopted in that era for higher-end systems before becoming standard by the mid 2010s.
[src:robyn-python/multi-core-processor] In the late 2010s, hexa-core (six cores) started entering the mainstream and since the early 2020s has overtaken quad-core in many spaces.
[src:robyn-python/multi-core-processor] The terms *multi-core* and *dual-core* most commonly refer to central processing units (CPUs), but are sometimes applied to digital signal processors (DSPs) and systems on chip (SoCs).
[src:robyn-python/multi-core-processor] The terms are generally used only to refer to multi-core microprocessors that are manufactured on the *same* integrated circuit die; separate microprocessor dies in the same package are generally referred to by another name, such as *multi-chip module*.
[src:robyn-python/multi-core-processor] This article uses the terms "multi-core" and "dual-core" for CPUs manufactured on the *same* integrated circuit, unless otherwise noted.
[src:robyn-python/multi-core-processor] In contrast to multi-core systems, the term *multi-CPU* refers to multiple physically separate processing-units (which often contain special circuitry to facilitate communication between each other).
[src:robyn-python/multi-core-processor] The terms *many-core* and *massively multi-core* are sometimes used to describe multi-core architectures with an especially high number of cores (tens to thousands).
[src:robyn-python/multi-core-processor] Some systems use many soft microprocessor cores placed on a single FPGA.
[src:robyn-python/multi-core-processor] Each "core" can be considered a "semiconductor intellectual property core" as well as a CPU core.
[src:robyn-python/multi-core-processor] While manufacturing technology improves, reducing the size of individual gates, physical limits of semiconductor-based microelectronics have become a major design concern.
[src:robyn-python/multi-core-processor] These physical limitations can cause significant heat dissipation and data synchronization problems.
[src:robyn-python/multi-core-processor] Various other methods are used to improve CPU performance.
[src:robyn-python/multi-core-processor] Some instruction-level parallelism (ILP) methods such as superscalar pipelining are suitable for many applications, but are inefficient for others that contain difficult-to-predict code.
[src:robyn-python/multi-core-processor] Many applications are better suited to thread-level parallelism (TLP) methods, and multiple independent CPUs are commonly used to increase a system's overall TLP.
[src:robyn-python/multi-core-processor] A combination of increased available space (due to refined manufacturing processes) and the demand for increased TLP led to the development of multi-core CPUs.
[src:robyn-python/multi-core-processor] In 1985, Apple engineer Sam Holland convinced Apple to develop its own 4-processor CPU chip to power future Macs called Scorpius.
[src:robyn-python/multi-core-processor] The processor's proposed feature set was highly ambitious, including four cores and SIMD (vector) support with inter-processor communication features.
[src:robyn-python/multi-core-processor] With the design beyond the fabrication capabilities of the time, the project was brought to an end in 1989.
[src:robyn-python/multi-core-processor] In the 1990s, Kunle Olukotun led the Stanford Hydra Chip Multiprocessor (CMP) research project.
[src:robyn-python/multi-core-processor] This initiative was among the first to demonstrate the viability of integrating multiple processors on a single chip, a concept that laid the groundwork for today's multicore processors.
[src:robyn-python/multi-core-processor] The Hydra project introduced support for thread-level speculation (TLS), enabling more efficient parallel execution of programs.
[src:robyn-python/multi-core-processor] Several business motives drive the development of multi-core architectures.
[src:robyn-python/multi-core-processor] For decades, it was possible to improve performance of a CPU by shrinking the area of the integrated circuit (IC), which reduced the cost per device on the IC.
[src:robyn-python/multi-core-processor] Alternatively, for the same circuit area, more transistors could be used in the design, which increased functionality, especially for complex instruction set computing (CISC) architectures.
[src:robyn-python/multi-core-processor] Clock rates also increased by orders of magnitude in the decades of the late 20th century, from several megahertz in the 1980s to several gigahertz in the early 2000s.
[src:robyn-python/multi-core-processor] As the rate of clock speed improvements slowed, increased use of parallel computing in the form of multi-core processors has been pursued to improve overall processing performance.
[src:robyn-python/multi-core-processor] Multiple cores were used on the same CPU chip, which could then lead to better sales of CPU chips with two or more cores.
[src:robyn-python/multi-core-processor] For example, Intel has produced a 48-core processor for research in cloud computing; each core has an x86 architecture.
[src:robyn-python/multi-core-processor] Since computer manufacturers have long implemented symmetric multiprocessing (SMP) designs using discrete CPUs, the issues regarding implementing multi-core processor architecture and supporting it with software are well known.
[src:robyn-python/multi-core-processor] The *ILP wall*; the increasing difficulty of finding enough parallelism in a single instruction stream to keep a high-performance single-core processor busy.
[src:robyn-python/multi-core-processor] The *power wall*; the trend of consuming exponentially increasing power (and thus also generating exponentially increasing heat) with each factorial increase of operating frequency.
[src:robyn-python/multi-core-processor] This increase can be mitigated by "shrinking" the processor by using smaller traces for the same logic.
[src:robyn-python/multi-core-processor] The *power wall* poses manufacturing, system design and deployment problems that have not been justified in the face of the diminished gains in performance due to the *memory wall* and *ILP wall*.
[src:robyn-python/multi-core-processor] In order to continue delivering regular performance improvements for general-purpose processors, manufacturers such as Intel and AMD have turned to multi-core designs, sacrificing lower manufacturing-costs for higher performance in some applications and systems.
[src:robyn-python/multi-core-processor] Multi-core architectures are being developed, but so are the alternatives.
[src:robyn-python/multi-core-processor] An especially strong contender for established markets is the further integration of peripheral functions into the chip.
[src:robyn-python/multi-core-processor] The proximity of multiple CPU cores on the same die allows the cache coherency circuitry to operate at a much higher clock rate than what is possible if the signals have to travel off-chip.
[src:robyn-python/multi-core-processor] Combining equivalent CPUs on a single die significantly improves the performance of cache snoop (alternative: Bus snooping) operations.
[src:robyn-python/multi-core-processor] Put simply, this means that signals between different CPUs travel shorter distances, and therefore those signals degrade less.
[src:robyn-python/multi-core-processor] These higher-quality signals allow more data to be sent in a given time period, since individual signals can be shorter and do not need to be repeated as often.
[src:robyn-python/multi-core-processor] Assuming that the die can physically fit into the package, multi-core CPU designs require much less printed circuit board (PCB) space than do multi-chip SMP designs.
[src:robyn-python/multi-core-processor] Also, a dual-core processor uses slightly less power than two coupled single-core processors, principally because of the decreased power required to drive signals external to the chip.
[src:robyn-python/multi-core-processor] Furthermore, the cores share some circuitry, like the L2 cache and the interface to the front-side bus (FSB).
[src:robyn-python/multi-core-processor] In terms of competing technologies for the available silicon die area, multi-core design can make use of proven CPU core library designs and produce a product with lower risk of design error than devising a new wider-core design.
[src:robyn-python/multi-core-processor] Also, adding more cache suffers from diminishing returns.
[src:robyn-python/multi-core-processor] Multi-core chips also allow higher performance at lower energy.
[src:robyn-python/multi-core-processor] This can be a big factor in mobile devices that operate on batteries.
[src:robyn-python/multi-core-processor] Since each core in a multi-core CPU is generally more energy-efficient, the chip becomes more efficient than having a single large monolithic core.
[src:robyn-python/multi-core-processor] This allows higher performance with less energy.
[src:robyn-python/multi-core-processor] A challenge in this, however, is the additional overhead of writing parallel code.
[src:robyn-python/multi-core-processor] Maximizing the usage of the computing resources provided by multi-core processors requires adjustments both to the operating system (OS) support and to existing application software.
[src:robyn-python/multi-core-processor] Also, the ability of multi-core processors to increase application performance depends on the use of multiple threads within applications.
[src:robyn-python/multi-core-processor] Integration of a multi-core chip can lower the chip production yields.
[src:robyn-python/multi-core-processor] They are also more difficult to manage thermally than lower-density single-core designs.
[src:robyn-python/multi-core-processor] From an architectural point of view, ultimately, single CPU designs may make better use of the silicon surface area than multiprocessing cores, so a development commitment to this architecture may carry the risk of obsolescence.
[src:robyn-python/multi-core-processor] Finally, raw processing power is not the only constraint on system performance.
[src:robyn-python/multi-core-processor] Two processing cores sharing the same system bus and memory bandwidth limits the real-world performance advantage.
[src:robyn-python/multi-core-processor] The trend in processor development has been towards an ever-increasing number of cores, as processors with hundreds or even thousands of cores become theoretically possible.
[src:robyn-python/multi-core-processor] In addition, multi-core chips mixed with simultaneous multithreading, memory-on-chip, and special-purpose "heterogeneous" (or asymmetric) cores promise further performance and efficiency gains, especially in processing multimedia, recognition and networking applications.
[src:robyn-python/multi-core-processor] For example, a big.LITTLE core includes a high-performance core (called 'big') and a low-power core (called 'LITTLE').
[src:robyn-python/multi-core-processor] There is also a trend towards improving energy-efficiency by focusing on performance-per-watt with advanced fine-grain or ultra fine-grain power management and dynamic voltage and frequency scaling (i.e. laptop computers and portable media players).
[src:robyn-python/multi-core-processor] Chips designed from the outset for a large number of cores (rather than having evolved from single core designs) are sometimes referred to as manycore designs, emphasising qualitative differences.
[src:robyn-python/multi-core-processor] The composition and balance of the cores in multi-core architecture show great variety.
[src:robyn-python/multi-core-processor] Some architectures use one core design repeated consistently ("homogeneous"), while others use a mixture of different cores, each optimized for a different, "heterogeneous" role.
[src:robyn-python/multi-core-processor] How multiple cores are implemented and integrated significantly affects both the developer's programming skills and the consumer's expectations of apps and interactivity versus the device.
[src:robyn-python/multi-core-processor] A device advertised as being octa-core will only have independent cores if advertised as *True Octa-core*, or similar styling, as opposed to being merely two sets of quad-cores each with fixed clock speeds.
[src:robyn-python/multi-core-processor] An outdated version of an anti-virus application may create a new thread for a scan process, while its GUI thread waits for commands from the user (e.g. cancel the scan).
[src:robyn-python/multi-core-processor] In such cases, a multi-core architecture is of little benefit for the application itself due to the single thread doing all the heavy lifting and the inability to balance the work evenly across multiple cores.
[src:robyn-python/multi-core-processor] Programming truly multithreaded code often requires complex co-ordination of threads and can easily introduce subtle and difficult-to-find bugs due to the interweaving of processing on data shared between threads (see thread-safety).
[src:robyn-python/multi-core-processor] Consequently, such code is much more difficult to debug than single-threaded code when it breaks.
[src:robyn-python/multi-core-processor] There has been a perceived lack of motivation for writing consumer-level threaded applications because of the relative rarity of consumer-level demand for maximum use of computer hardware.
[src:robyn-python/multi-core-processor] Also, serial tasks like decoding the entropy encoding algorithms used in video codecs are impossible to parallelize because each result generated is used to help create the next result of the entropy decoding algorithm.
[src:robyn-python/multi-core-processor] If developers are unable to design software to fully exploit the resources provided by multiple cores, then they will ultimately reach an insurmountable performance ceiling.
[src:robyn-python/multi-core-processor] The telecommunications market had been one of the first that needed a new design of parallel datapath packet processing because there was a very quick adoption of these multiple-core processors for the datapath and the control plane.
[src:robyn-python/multi-core-processor] These MPUs are going to replace the traditional Network Processors that were based on proprietary microcode or picocode.
[src:robyn-python/multi-core-processor] Parallel programming techniques can benefit from multiple cores directly.
[src:robyn-python/multi-core-processor] Some existing parallel programming models such as Cilk Plus, OpenMP, OpenHMPP, FastFlow, Skandium, MPI, and Erlang can be used on multi-core platforms.
[src:robyn-python/multi-core-processor] Intel introduced a new abstraction for C++ parallelism called TBB.
[src:robyn-python/multi-core-processor] Other research efforts include the Codeplay Sieve System, Cray's Chapel, Sun's Fortress, and IBM's X10.
[src:robyn-python/multi-core-processor] Multi-core processing has also affected the ability of modern computational software development.
[src:robyn-python/multi-core-processor] Developers programming in newer languages might find that their modern languages do not support multi-core functionality.
[src:robyn-python/multi-core-processor] This then requires the use of numerical libraries to access code written in languages like C and Fortran, which perform math computations faster than newer languages like C#.
[src:robyn-python/multi-core-processor] Intel's MKL and AMD's ACML are written in these native languages and take advantage of multi-core processing.
[src:robyn-python/multi-core-processor] Balancing the application workload across processors can be problematic, especially if they have different performance characteristics.
[src:robyn-python/multi-core-processor] There are different conceptual models to deal with the problem, for example using a coordination language and program building blocks (programming libraries or higher-order functions).
[src:robyn-python/multi-core-processor] Each block can have a different native implementation for each processor type.
[src:robyn-python/multi-core-processor] Users simply program using these abstractions and an intelligent compiler chooses the best implementation based on the context.
[src:robyn-python/multi-core-processor] Managing concurrency acquires a central role in developing parallel applications.
[src:robyn-python/multi-core-processor] The partitioning stage of a design is intended to expose opportunities for parallel execution.
[src:robyn-python/multi-core-processor] Hence, the focus is on defining a large number of small tasks in order to yield what is termed a fine-grained decomposition of a problem.
[src:robyn-python/multi-core-processor] The tasks generated by a partition are intended to execute concurrently but cannot, in general, execute independently.
[src:robyn-python/multi-core-processor] The computation to be performed in one task will typically require data associated with another task.
[src:robyn-python/multi-core-processor] Data must then be transferred between tasks so as to allow computation to proceed.
[src:robyn-python/multi-core-processor] This information flow is specified in the communication phase of a design.
[src:robyn-python/multi-core-processor] In the third stage, development moves from the abstract toward the concrete.
[src:robyn-python/multi-core-processor] Developers revisit decisions made in the partitioning and communication phases with a view to obtaining an algorithm that will execute efficiently on some class of parallel computer.
[src:robyn-python/multi-core-processor] In particular, developers consider whether it is useful to combine, or agglomerate, tasks identified by the partitioning phase, so as to provide a smaller number of tasks, each of greater size.
[src:robyn-python/multi-core-processor] They also determine whether it is worthwhile to replicate data and computation.
[src:robyn-python/multi-core-processor] In the fourth and final stage of the design of parallel algorithms, the developers specify where each task is to execute.
[src:robyn-python/multi-core-processor] This mapping problem does not arise on uniprocessors or on shared-memory computers that provide automatic task scheduling.
[src:robyn-python/multi-core-processor] On the other hand, on the server side, multi-core processors are ideal because they allow many users to connect to a site simultaneously and have independent threads of execution.
[src:robyn-python/multi-core-processor] This allows for Web servers and application servers that have much better throughput.
[src:robyn-python/multi-core-processor] Vendors may license some software "per processor".
[src:robyn-python/multi-core-processor] This can give rise to ambiguity, because a "processor" may consist either of a single core or of a combination of cores.
[src:robyn-python/multi-core-processor] Embedded computing operates in an area of processor technology distinct from that of "mainstream" PCs.
[src:robyn-python/multi-core-processor] The same technological drives towards multi-core apply here too.
[src:robyn-python/multi-core-processor] Indeed, in many cases the application is a "natural" fit for multi-core technologies, if the task can easily be partitioned between the different processors.
[src:robyn-python/multi-core-processor] In addition, embedded software is typically developed for a specific hardware release, making issues of software portability, legacy code or supporting independent developers less critical than is the case for PC or enterprise computing.
[src:robyn-python/multi-core-processor] As a result, it is easier for developers to adopt new technologies and as a result there is a greater variety of multi-core processing architectures and suppliers.
[src:robyn-python/multi-core-processor] As of 2010, multi-core network processors have become mainstream, with companies such as Freescale Semiconductor, Cavium Networks, Wintegra and Broadcom all manufacturing products with eight processors.
[src:robyn-python/multi-core-processor] For the system developer, a key challenge is how to exploit all the cores in these devices to achieve maximum networking performance at the system level, despite the performance limitations inherent in a symmetric multiprocessing (SMP) operating system.
[src:robyn-python/multi-core-processor] Companies such as 6WIND provide portable packet processing software designed so that the networking data plane runs in a fast path environment outside the operating system of the network device.
[src:robyn-python/multi-core-processor] In digital signal processing the same trend applies: Texas Instruments has the three-core TMS320C6488 and four-core TMS320C5441, Freescale the four-core MSC8144 and six-core MSC8156 (and both have stated they are working on eight-core successors).
[src:robyn-python/multi-core-processor] Newer entries include the Storm-1 family from Stream Processors, Inc with 40 and 80 general purpose ALUs per chip, all programmable in C as a SIMD engine and Picochip with 300 processors on a single die, focused on communication applications.
[src:robyn-python/multi-core-processor] In heterogeneous computing, where a system uses more than one kind of processor or cores, multi-core solutions are becoming more common: Xilinx Zynq UltraScale+ MPSoC has a quad-core ARM Cortex-A53 and dual-core ARM Cortex-R5.
[src:robyn-python/multi-core-processor] Software solutions such as OpenAMP are being used to help with inter-processor communication.
[src:robyn-python/multi-core-processor] Mobile devices may use the ARM big.LITTLE architecture.
[src:robyn-python/multi-core-processor] The research and development of multicore processors often compares many options, and benchmarks are developed to help such evaluations.
[src:robyn-python/multi-core-processor] Existing benchmarks include SPLASH-2, PARSEC, and COSMIC for heterogeneous systems.
[src:robyn-python/python-programming-language] Guido van Rossum began working on Python in the late 1980s as a successor to the ABC programming language.
[src:robyn-python/python-programming-language] Python 3.0, released in 2008, was a major revision and not completely backward-compatible with earlier versions.
[src:robyn-python/python-programming-language] Beginning with Python 3.5, capabilities and keywords for typing were added to the language, allowing optional static typing.
[src:robyn-python/python-programming-language] As of 2026, the Python Software Foundation supports Python 3.10, 3.11, 3.12, 3.13, and 3.14, following the project's annual release cycle and five-year support policy.
[src:robyn-python/python-programming-language] Python 3.15 is currently in the beta development phase, and the stable release is expected to launch in October 2026.
[src:robyn-python/python-programming-language] Earlier versions in the 3.x series have reached end-of-life and no longer receive security updates.
[src:robyn-python/python-programming-language] Python has gained extensive use in the machine learning community.
[src:robyn-python/python-programming-language] It is widely taught as an introductory programming language.
[src:robyn-python/python-programming-language] Since 2003, Python has consistently ranked among the top ten most popular programming languages in the TIOBE Programming Community Index, which ranks programming languages based on searches across 24 platforms.
[src:robyn-python/python-programming-language] Python was conceived in the late 1980s by Guido van Rossum at Centrum Wiskunde & Informatica (CWI) in the Netherlands.
[src:robyn-python/python-programming-language] It was designed as a successor to the ABC programming language, which was inspired by SETL, capable of exception handling and interfacing with the Amoeba operating system.
[src:robyn-python/python-programming-language] Python implementation began in December 1989.
[src:robyn-python/python-programming-language] Van Rossum first released it in 1991 as Python 0.9.0.
[src:robyn-python/python-programming-language] In January 2019, active Python core developers elected a five-member Steering Council to lead the project.
[src:robyn-python/python-programming-language] The name *Python* derives from the British comedy series *Monty Python's Flying Circus*.
[src:robyn-python/python-programming-language] Python 2.0 was released on 16 October 2000, featuring many new features such as list comprehensions, cycle-detecting garbage collection, reference counting, and Unicode support.
[src:robyn-python/python-programming-language] Python 2.7's end-of-life was initially set for 2015, and then postponed to 2020 out of concern that a large body of existing code could not easily be forward-ported to Python 3.
[src:robyn-python/python-programming-language] It no longer receives security patches or updates.
[src:robyn-python/python-programming-language] While Python 2.7 and older versions are officially unsupported, a different unofficial Python implementation, PyPy, continues to support Python 2, i.e., "2.7.18+" (plus 3.11), with the plus signifying (at least some) "backported security updates".
[src:robyn-python/python-programming-language] Python 3.0 was released on 3 December 2008, and was a major revision and not completely backward-compatible with earlier versions, with some new semantics and changed syntax.
[src:robyn-python/python-programming-language] Python 2.7.18, released in 2020, was the last release of Python 2.
[src:robyn-python/python-programming-language] Several releases in the Python 3.x series have added new syntax to the language, and made a few (considered very minor) backward-incompatible changes.
[src:robyn-python/python-programming-language] As of May 2026, Python 3.14.6 is the latest stable release.
[src:robyn-python/python-programming-language] All older 3.x versions had a security update down to Python 3.9.24 then again with 3.9.25, the final version in 3.9 series.
[src:robyn-python/python-programming-language] Python 3.10 is, since November 2025, the oldest supported branch.
[src:robyn-python/python-programming-language] Python 3.15 has an alpha released, and Android has an official downloadable executable available for Python 3.14.
[src:robyn-python/python-programming-language] Releases receive two years of full support followed by three years of security support.
[src:robyn-python/python-programming-language] Python is a multi-paradigm programming language.
[src:robyn-python/python-programming-language] Object-oriented programming and structured programming are fully supported, and many of their features support functional programming and aspect-oriented programming – including metaprogramming and metaobjects.
[src:robyn-python/python-programming-language] Many other paradigms are supported via extensions, including design by contract and logic programming.
[src:robyn-python/python-programming-language] Python is often referred to as a *'glue language'* because it is purposely designed to be able to integrate components written in other languages.
[src:robyn-python/python-programming-language] Python uses dynamic typing and a combination of reference counting and a cycle-detecting garbage collector for memory management.
[src:robyn-python/python-programming-language] It uses dynamic name resolution (late binding), which binds method and variable names during program execution.
[src:robyn-python/python-programming-language] Python's design offers some support for functional programming in the "Lisp tradition".
[src:robyn-python/python-programming-language] It has `filter`, `map`, and `reduce` functions; list comprehensions, dictionaries, sets, and generator expressions.
[src:robyn-python/python-programming-language] The standard library has two modules (`itertools` and `functools`) that implement functional tools borrowed from Haskell and Standard ML.
[src:robyn-python/python-programming-language] However, Python has received criticism for violating these principles and adding unnecessary language bloat.
[src:robyn-python/python-programming-language] Responses to these criticisms note that the Zen of Python is a guideline rather than a rule.
[src:robyn-python/python-programming-language] The addition of some new features had been controversial: Guido van Rossum resigned as *Benevolent Dictator for Life* after conflict about adding the assignment expression operator in Python 3.8.
[src:robyn-python/python-programming-language] Nevertheless, rather than building all functionality into its core, Python was designed to be highly extensible through modules.
[src:robyn-python/python-programming-language] This compact modularity has made it particularly popular as a means of adding programmable interfaces to existing applications.
[src:robyn-python/python-programming-language] Van Rossum's vision of a small core language with a large standard library and an easily extensible interpreter stemmed from his frustrations with ABC, which represented the opposite approach.
[src:robyn-python/python-programming-language] Python claims to strive for a simpler, less-cluttered syntax and grammar, while giving developers a choice in their coding methodology.
[src:robyn-python/python-programming-language] Python lacks `do .. while` loops, which Rossum considered harmful.
[src:robyn-python/python-programming-language] In contrast to Perl's motto "there is more than one way to do it", Python advocates an approach where "there should be one – and preferably only one – obvious way to do it".
[src:robyn-python/python-programming-language] In practice, however, Python provides many ways to achieve a given goal.
[src:robyn-python/python-programming-language] There are at least three ways to format a string literal, with no certainty as to which one a programmer should use.
[src:robyn-python/python-programming-language] Python's developers typically prioritize readability over performance.
[src:robyn-python/python-programming-language] For example, they reject patches to non-critical parts of the CPython reference implementation that would offer increases in speed that do not justify the cost of clarity and readability.
[src:robyn-python/python-programming-language] Execution speed can be improved by moving speed-critical functions to extension modules written in languages such as C, or by using a just-in-time compiler like PyPy.
[src:robyn-python/python-programming-language] Also, it is possible to transpile to other languages.
[src:robyn-python/python-programming-language] However, this approach either fails to achieve the expected speed-up, since Python is a very dynamic language, or only a restricted subset of Python is compiled (with potential minor semantic changes).
[src:robyn-python/python-programming-language] Python is meant to be a fun language to use.
[src:robyn-python/python-programming-language] This goal is reflected in the name – a tribute to the British comedy group Monty Python – and in playful approaches to some tutorials and reference materials.
[src:robyn-python/python-programming-language] For instance, some code examples use the terms "spam" and "eggs" (in reference to a Monty Python sketch), rather than the typical terms "foo" and "bar".
[src:robyn-python/python-programming-language] A common neologism in the Python community is *pythonic*, which has a broad range of meanings related to program style: Pythonic code may use Python idioms well; be natural or show fluency in the language; or conform with Python's minimalist philosophy and emphasis on readability.
[src:robyn-python/python-programming-language] There are 3 kinds of PEPs, with those are being *standards track PEP*, *Informational PEP* and *Process PEP*s which has their own unique meanings.
[src:robyn-python/python-programming-language] They were firstly introduced in 2000, inspired by other RfCs (requests for comments) and Desing Enhancement Proposals.
[src:robyn-python/python-programming-language] Most known PEPs are PEP – 1, PEP – 8, PEP – 20, PEP – 257 and others.
[src:robyn-python/python-programming-language] Python is meant to be an easily readable language.
[src:robyn-python/python-programming-language] Its formatting is visually uncluttered and often uses English keywords where other languages use punctuation.
[src:robyn-python/python-programming-language] Unlike many other languages, it does not use curly brackets to delimit blocks, and semicolons after statements are allowed but rarely used.
[src:robyn-python/python-programming-language] It has fewer syntactic exceptions and special cases than C or Pascal.
[src:robyn-python/python-programming-language] Python uses whitespace indentation, rather than curly brackets or keywords, to delimit blocks.
[src:robyn-python/python-programming-language] An increase in indentation comes after certain statements; a decrease in indentation signifies the end of the current block.
[src:robyn-python/python-programming-language] Thus, the program's visual structure accurately represents its semantic structure.
[src:robyn-python/python-programming-language] This feature is sometimes termed the off-side rule.
[src:robyn-python/python-programming-language] Some other languages use indentation this way; but in most, indentation has no semantic meaning.
[src:robyn-python/python-programming-language] The recommended indent size is four spaces.
[src:robyn-python/python-programming-language] The assignment statement (`=`) binds a name as a reference to a separate, dynamically allocated object.
[src:robyn-python/python-programming-language] Variables may subsequently be rebound at any time to any object.
[src:robyn-python/python-programming-language] In Python, a variable name is a generic reference holder without a fixed data type; however, it always refers to *some* object with a type.
[src:robyn-python/python-programming-language] This is called dynamic typing—in contrast to statically-typed languages, where each variable may contain only a value of a certain type.
[src:robyn-python/python-programming-language] Python does not support tail call optimization or first-class continuations; according to Van Rossum, the language never will.
[src:robyn-python/python-programming-language] However, better support for coroutine-like functionality is provided by extending Python's generators.
[src:robyn-python/python-programming-language] Before 2.5, generators were lazy iterators; data was passed unidirectionally out of the generator.
[src:robyn-python/python-programming-language] From Python 2.5 on, it is possible to pass data back into a generator function; and from version 3.3, data can be passed through multiple stack levels.
[src:robyn-python/python-programming-language] In Python, a distinction between expressions and statements is rigidly enforced, in contrast to languages such as Common Lisp, Scheme, or Ruby.
[src:robyn-python/python-programming-language] A statement cannot be part of an expression; because of this restriction, expressions such as list and `dict` comprehensions (and lambda expressions) cannot contain statements.
[src:robyn-python/python-programming-language] As a particular case, an assignment statement such as `a = 1` cannot be part of the conditional expression of a conditional statement.
[src:robyn-python/python-programming-language] Python uses duck typing, and it has typed objects but untyped variable names.
[src:robyn-python/python-programming-language] Type constraints are not checked at definition time; rather, operations on an object may fail at usage time, indicating that the object is not of an appropriate type.
[src:robyn-python/python-programming-language] Despite being dynamically typed, Python is strongly typed, forbidding operations that are poorly defined (e.g., adding a number and a string) rather than quietly attempting to interpret them.
[src:robyn-python/python-programming-language] Python allows programmers to define their own types using classes, most often for object-oriented programming.
[src:robyn-python/python-programming-language] New instances of classes are constructed by calling the class, for example, `SpamClass()` or `EggsClass()`); the classes are instances of the metaclass `type` (which is an instance of itself), thereby allowing metaprogramming and reflection.
[src:robyn-python/python-programming-language] Before version 3.0, Python had two kinds of classes, both using the same syntax: *old-style* and *new-style*.
[src:robyn-python/python-programming-language] Current Python versions support the semantics of only the new style.
[src:robyn-python/python-programming-language] Python supports optional type annotations.
[src:robyn-python/python-programming-language] These annotations are not enforced by the language, but may be used by external tools such as **mypy** to catch errors.
[src:robyn-python/python-programming-language] Python includes a module `typing` including several type names for type annotations.
[src:robyn-python/python-programming-language] Also, mypy supports a Python compiler called mypyc, which leverages type annotations for optimization.
[src:robyn-python/python-programming-language] Python includes conventional symbols for arithmetic operators (`+`, `-`, `*`, `/`), the floor-division operator `//`, and the modulo operator `%`.
[src:robyn-python/python-programming-language] (With the modulo operator, a remainder can be negative, e.g., `4 % -3 == -2`.) Python also offers the `**` symbol for exponentiation, e.g.
[src:robyn-python/python-programming-language] These operators work as in traditional mathematics; with the same precedence rules, the infix operators `+` and `-` can also be unary, to represent positive and negative numbers respectively.
[src:robyn-python/python-programming-language] Division between integers produces floating-point results.
[src:robyn-python/python-programming-language] In Python terms, the `/` operator represents *true division* (or simply *division*), while the `//` operator represents *floor division.* Before version 3.0, the `/` operator represents *classic division*.
[src:robyn-python/python-programming-language] Rounding towards negative infinity, though a different method than in most languages, adds consistency to Python.
[src:robyn-python/python-programming-language] For instance, this rounding implies that the equation `(a + b)//b == a//b + 1` is always true.
[src:robyn-python/python-programming-language] Also, the rounding implies that the equation `b*(a//b) + a%b == a` is valid for both positive and negative values of `a`.
[src:robyn-python/python-programming-language] As expected, the result of `a%b` lies in the half-open interval [0, *b*), where `b` is a positive integer; however, maintaining the validity of the equation requires that the result must lie in the interval (*b*, 0] when `b` is negative.
[src:robyn-python/python-programming-language] Python provides a `round` function for rounding a float to the nearest integer.
[src:robyn-python/python-programming-language] For tie-breaking, Python 3 uses the *round to even* method: `round(1.5)` and `round(2.5)` both produce `2`.
[src:robyn-python/python-programming-language] Python allows Boolean expressions that contain multiple equality relations to be consistent with general usage in mathematics.
[src:robyn-python/python-programming-language] For example, the expression `a < b < c` tests whether `a` is less than `b` and `b` is less than `c`.
[src:robyn-python/python-programming-language] C-derived languages interpret this expression differently: in C, the expression would first evaluate `a < b`, resulting in 0 or 1, and that result would then be compared with `c`.
[src:robyn-python/python-programming-language] Python uses arbitrary-precision arithmetic for all integer operations.
[src:robyn-python/python-programming-language] The `Decimal` type/class in the `decimal` module provides decimal floating-point numbers to a pre-defined arbitrary precision with several rounding modes.
[src:robyn-python/python-programming-language] The `Fraction` class in the `fractions` module provides arbitrary precision for rational numbers.
[src:robyn-python/python-programming-language] Due to Python's extensive mathematics library and the third-party library NumPy, the language is frequently used for scientific scripting in tasks such as numerical data processing and manipulation.
[src:robyn-python/python-programming-language] Functions are created in Python by using the `def` keyword.
[src:robyn-python/python-programming-language] A function is defined similarly to how it is called, by first providing the function name and then the required parameters.
[src:robyn-python/python-programming-language] To assign a default value to a function parameter in case no actual value is provided at run time, variable-definition syntax can be used inside the function header.
[src:robyn-python/python-programming-language] Python's large standard library is commonly cited as one of its greatest strengths.
[src:robyn-python/python-programming-language] For Internet-facing applications, many standard formats and protocols such as MIME and HTTP are supported.
[src:robyn-python/python-programming-language] The language includes modules for creating graphical user interfaces, connecting to relational databases, generating pseudorandom numbers, arithmetic with arbitrary-precision decimals, manipulating regular expressions, and unit testing.
[src:robyn-python/python-programming-language] Some parts of the standard library are covered by specifications—for example, the Web Server Gateway Interface (WSGI) implementation `wsgiref` follows PEP 333—but most parts are specified by their code, internal documentation, and test suites.
[src:robyn-python/python-programming-language] However, because most of the standard library is cross-platform Python code, only a few modules must be altered or rewritten for variant implementations.
[src:robyn-python/python-programming-language] As of 13 March 2025, the Python Package Index (PyPI), the official repository for third-party Python software, contains over 614,339 packages.
[src:robyn-python/python-programming-language] Most Python implementations (including CPython) include a read–eval–print loop (REPL); this permits the environment to function as a command line interpreter, with which users enter statements sequentially and receive results immediately.
[src:robyn-python/python-programming-language] Also, CPython is bundled with an integrated development environment (IDE) called IDLE, which is oriented toward beginners.
[src:robyn-python/python-programming-language] Other shells, including IDLE and IPython, add additional capabilities such as improved auto-completion, session-state retention, and syntax highlighting.
[src:robyn-python/python-programming-language] CPython is the reference implementation of Python.
[src:robyn-python/python-programming-language] This implementation is written in C, meeting the C11 standard since version 3.11.
[src:robyn-python/python-programming-language] Older versions use the C89 standard with several select C99 features, but third-party extensions are not limited to older C versions—e.g., they can be implemented using C11 or C++.
[src:robyn-python/python-programming-language] CPython compiles Python programs into an intermediate bytecode, which is then executed by a virtual machine.
[src:robyn-python/python-programming-language] CPython is distributed with a large standard library written in a combination of C and native Python.
[src:robyn-python/python-programming-language] CPython is available for many platforms, including Windows and most modern Unix-like systems, including macOS (and Apple M1 Macs, since Python 3.9.1, using an experimental installer).
[src:robyn-python/python-programming-language] Starting with Python 3.9, the Python installer intentionally fails to install on Windows 7 and 8; Windows XP was supported until Python 3.5.
[src:robyn-python/python-programming-language] Old Python versions unofficially support VMS (mostly supporting) and OpenVMS x86-64 has Python 3.10 support.
[src:robyn-python/python-programming-language] Platform portability was one of Python's earliest priorities.
[src:robyn-python/python-programming-language] During development of Python 1 and 2, even OS/2 and Solaris were supported; since that time, support has been dropped for many platforms.
[src:robyn-python/python-programming-language] All current Python versions (since 3.7) support only operating systems that feature multithreading, by now supporting not nearly as many operating systems (dropping many outdated) than in the past.
[src:robyn-python/python-programming-language] All alternative implementations have at least slightly different semantics.
[src:robyn-python/python-programming-language] For example, an alternative may include unordered dictionaries, in contrast to other current Python versions.
[src:robyn-python/python-programming-language] As another example in the larger Python ecosystem, PyPy does not support the full C Python API.
[src:robyn-python/python-programming-language] Creating an executable with Python often is done by bundling an entire Python interpreter into the executable, which causes binary sizes to be massive for small programs, yet there exist implementations that are capable of truly compiling Python.
[src:robyn-python/python-programming-language] Stackless Python is a significant fork of CPython that implements microthreads.
[src:robyn-python/python-programming-language] This implementation uses the call stack differently, thus allowing massively concurrent programs.
[src:robyn-python/python-programming-language] A performance comparison among various Python implementations, using a non-numerical (combinatorial) workload, was presented at EuroSciPy '13.
[src:robyn-python/python-programming-language] In addition, Python's performance relative to other programming languages is benchmarked by The Computer Language Benchmarks Game.
[src:robyn-python/python-programming-language] There are several approaches to optimizing Python performance, despite the inherent slowness of an interpreted language.
[src:robyn-python/python-programming-language] Python's development is conducted mostly through the *Python Enhancement Proposal* (PEP) process; this process is the primary mechanism for proposing major new features, collecting community input on issues, and documenting Python design decisions.
[src:robyn-python/python-programming-language] Python coding style is covered in PEP 8.
[src:robyn-python/python-programming-language] Outstanding PEPs are reviewed and commented on by the Python community and the steering council.
[src:robyn-python/python-programming-language] Enhancement of the language corresponds with development of the CPython reference implementation.
[src:robyn-python/python-programming-language] The mailing list python-dev is the primary forum for the language's development.
[src:robyn-python/python-programming-language] Specific issues were originally discussed in the Roundup bug tracker hosted by the foundation.
[src:robyn-python/python-programming-language] In 2022, all issues and discussions were migrated to GitHub.
[src:robyn-python/python-programming-language] Development originally took place on a self-hosted source-code repository running Mercurial, until Python moved to GitHub in January 2017.
[src:robyn-python/python-programming-language] Many alpha, beta, and release-candidates are also released as previews and for testing before final releases.
[src:robyn-python/python-programming-language] Although there is a rough schedule for releases, they are often delayed if the code is not ready yet.
[src:robyn-python/python-programming-language] Python's development team monitors the state of the code by running a large unit test suite during development.
[src:robyn-python/python-programming-language] The major academic conference on Python is PyCon.
[src:robyn-python/python-programming-language] Also, there are special Python mentoring programs, such as PyLadies.
[src:robyn-python/python-programming-language] Python's name is inspired by the British comedy group Monty Python, whom Python creator Guido van Rossum enjoyed while developing the language.
[src:robyn-python/python-programming-language] Monty Python references appear frequently in Python code and culture; for example, the metasyntactic variables often used in Python literature are *spam* and *eggs*, rather than the traditional *foo* and *bar*.
[src:robyn-python/python-programming-language] Also, the official Python documentation contains various references to Monty Python routines.
[src:robyn-python/python-programming-language] Python users are sometimes referred to as "Pythonistas".
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] Rust supports multiple programming paradigms.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] It was influenced by ideas from functional programming, including immutability, higher-order functions, algebraic data types, and pattern matching.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] It also supports object-oriented programming via structs, enums, traits, and methods.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] Rust enforces memory safety (i.e., that all references point to valid memory) without a conventional garbage collector; instead, memory safety errors and data races are prevented by the "borrow checker", which tracks the object lifetime of references at compile time.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] Software developer Graydon Hoare created Rust in 2006 while working at Mozilla, which officially sponsored the project in 2009.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] The first stable release, Rust 1.0, was published in May 2015.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] The project has been sponsored by the Rust Foundation since February 2021.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] Rust has been adopted by many software projects, especially web services and system software.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] It has been studied academically and has a growing community of developers.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] Rust began as a personal project by Mozilla employee Graydon Hoare in 2006.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] According to *MIT Technology Review*, he started the project due to his frustration with a broken elevator in his apartment building whose software had crashed, and named the language after the group of fungi of the same name that is "over-engineered for survival".
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] During the time period between 2006 and 2009, Rust was not publicized to others at Mozilla and was written in Hoare's free time; Hoare began speaking about the language around 2009 after a small group at Mozilla became interested in the project.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] Hoare cited languages from the 1970s, 1980s, and 1990s as influences — including CLU, BETA, Mesa, NIL, Erlang, Newsqueak, Napier, Hermes, Sather, Alef, and Limbo.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] During the early years, the Rust compiler was written in about 38,000 lines of OCaml.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] Early Rust contained several features no longer present today, including explicit object-oriented programming via an `obj` keyword and a typestates system for variable state changes, such as going from uninitialized to initialized.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] Mozilla officially sponsored the Rust project in 2009.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] Brendan Eich and other executives, intrigued by the possibility of using Rust for a safe web browser engine, placed engineers on the project including Patrick Walton, Niko Matsakis, Felix Klock, and Manish Goregaokar.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] A conference room taken by the project developers was dubbed "the nerd cave," with a sign placed outside the door.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] During this time period, work had shifted from the initial OCaml compiler to a self-hosting compiler (*i.e.*, written in Rust) targeting LLVM.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] The ownership system was in place by 2010.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] The Rust logo was developed in 2011 based on a bicycle chainring.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] Rust 0.1 became the first public release on January 20, 2012 for Windows, Linux, and MacOS.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] The early 2010s witnessed increasing involvement from full-time engineers at Mozilla and open source volunteers outside Mozilla.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] The years from 2012 to 2015 were marked by substantial changes to the Rust type system.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] Memory management through the ownership system was gradually consolidated and expanded.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] By 2013, the garbage collector was rarely used, and was removed in favor of the ownership system.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] Other features were removed in order to simplify the language, including typestates, the `pure` keyword, various specialized pointer types, and syntax support for channels.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] According to Steve Klabnik, Rust was influenced during this period by developers coming from C++ (e.g., low-level performance of features), scripting languages (e.g., Cargo and package management), and functional programming (e.g., type systems development).
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] Graydon Hoare stepped down from Rust in 2013.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] After Hoare's departure, it evolved organically under a federated governance structure, with a "core team" of initially six people, and around 30-40 developers total across various other teams.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] A Request for Comments (RFC) process for new language features was added in March 2014.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] The core team would grow to nine people by 2016 with over 1600 RFCs.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] Dobb's Journal* in January 2014, while Rust was "widely viewed as a remarkably elegant language", adoption slowed because it radically changed from version to version.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] Rust development at this time focused on finalizing features for version 1.0 so that it could begin promising backward compatibility.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] Six years after Mozilla's sponsorship, Rust 1.0 was published and became the first stable release on May 15, 2015.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] A year later, the Rust compiler had accumulated over 1,400 contributors, and there were over 5,000 third-party libraries published on the Rust package management website Crates.io.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] The development of the Servo browser engine continued in parallel with Rust, jointly funded by Mozilla and Samsung.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] The teams behind the two projects worked in close collaboration; new features in Rust were tested out by the Servo team, and new features in Servo were used to give feedback back to the Rust team.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] The first version of Servo was released in 2016.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] The Firefox web browser shipped with Rust code as of 2016 (version 45), but components of Servo did not appear in Firefox until September 2017 (version 57) as part of the Gecko and Quantum projects.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] Improvements were made to the Rust toolchain ecosystem during the years following 1.0 including Rustfmt, integrated development environment integration, and a regular compiler testing and release cycle.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] Rust's community gained a code of conduct and an IRC chat for discussion.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] The earliest known adoption outside of Mozilla was by individual projects at Samsung, Facebook (now Meta Platforms), Dropbox, and Tilde, Inc., the company behind ember.js.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] Engineers cited performance, lack of a garbage collector, safety, and pleasantness of working in the language as reasons for the adoption.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] Amazon developers cited a finding by Portuguese researchers that Rust code used less energy compared to similar code written in Java.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] In August 2020, Mozilla laid off 250 of its 1,000 employees worldwide, as part of a corporate restructuring caused by the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] The event raised concerns about the future of Rust.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] In the following week, the Rust Core Team acknowledged the severe impact of the layoffs and announced that plans for a Rust foundation were underway.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] The first goal of the foundation would be to take ownership of all trademarks and domain names and to take financial responsibility for their costs.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] On February 8, 2021, the formation of the Rust Foundation was announced by five founding companies: Amazon Web Services, Google, Huawei, Microsoft, and Mozilla.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] The foundation would provide financial support for Rust developers in the form of grants and server funding.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] In a blog post published on April 6, 2021, Google announced support for Rust within the Android Open Source Project as an alternative to C/C++.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] On November 22, 2021, the Moderation Team, which was responsible for enforcing the community code of conduct, announced their resignation "in protest of the Core Team placing themselves unaccountable to anyone but themselves".
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] In May 2022, members of the Rust leadership council posted a public response to the incident.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] The Rust Foundation posted a draft for a new trademark policy on April 6, 2023, which resulted in widespread negative reactions from Rust users and contributors.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] The trademark policy included rules for how the Rust logo and name could be used.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] Rust's syntax is similar to that of C and C++, although many of its features were influenced by functional programming languages such as OCaml.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] Hoare has described Rust as targeted at frustrated C++ developers.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] Below is a "Hello, World!" program in Rust.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] The `fn` keyword denotes a function, and the `println!` macro (see § Macros) prints the message to standard output.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] Statements in Rust are separated by semicolons.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] Variables in Rust are defined through the `let` keyword.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] The example below assigns a value to the variable with name `foo` of type `i32` and outputs its value; the type annotation `: i32` can be omitted.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] Variables are immutable by default, unless the `mut` keyword is added.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] The following example uses `//`, which denotes the start of a comment.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] Multiple `let` expressions can define multiple variables with the same name, known as variable shadowing.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] Variable shadowing allows transforming variables without having to name the variables differently.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] Variable shadowing is also possible for values of different types.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] A *block expression* is delimited by curly brackets.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] An `if` conditional expression executes code based on whether the given value is `true`.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] `else` can be used for when the value evaluates to `false`, and `else if` can be used for combining multiple expressions.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] `while` can be used to repeat a block of code while a condition is met.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] For loops in Rust loop over elements of a collection.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] `for` expressions work over any iterator type.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] In the above code, `4..=10` is a value of type `Range` which implements the `Iterator` trait.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] The code within the curly braces is applied to each element returned by the iterator.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] Iterators can be combined with functions over iterators like `map`, `filter`, and `sum`.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] More generally, the `loop` keyword allows repeating a portion of code until a `break` occurs.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] `break` may optionally exit the loop with a value.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] In the case of nested loops, labels denoted by `'label_name` can be used to break an outer loop rather than the innermost loop.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] The `match` and `if let` expressions can be used for pattern matching.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] Rust is strongly typed and statically typed, meaning that the types of all variables must be known at compilation time.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] Assigning a value of a particular type to a differently typed variable causes a compilation error.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] Type inference is used to determine the type of variables if unspecified.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] The type `()`, called the "unit type" in Rust, is a concrete type that has exactly one value.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] It occupies no memory (as it represents the absence of value).
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] All functions that do not have an indicated return type implicitly return `()`.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] It is similar to `void` in other C-style languages; however, `void` denotes the absence of a type and cannot have any value.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] The default integer type is `i32`, and the default floating point type is `f64`.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] If the type of a literal number is not explicitly provided, it is either inferred from the context or the default type is used.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] Integer types in Rust are named based on the signedness and the number of bits the type takes.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] For example, `i32` is a signed integer that takes 32 bits of storage, whereas `u8` is unsigned and only takes 8 bits of storage.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] `isize` and `usize` take storage depending on the memory address bus width of the compilation target.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] For example, when building for 32-bit targets, both types will take up 32 bits of space.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] By default, integer literals are in base-10, but different radices are supported with prefixes, for example, `0b11` for binary numbers, `0o567` for octals, and `0xDB` for hexadecimals.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] By default, integer literals default to `i32` as its type.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] Suffixes such as `4u32` can be used to explicitly set the type of a literal.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] Byte literals such as `b'X'` are available to represent the ASCII value (as a `u8`) of a specific character.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] The Boolean type is referred to as `bool` which can take a value of either `true` or `false`.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] A `char` takes up 32 bits of space and represents a Unicode scalar value: a Unicode codepoint that is not a surrogate.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] IEEE 754 floating point numbers are supported with `f32` for single precision floats and `f64` for double precision floats.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] Compound types can contain multiple values.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] Tuples are fixed-size lists that can contain values whose types can be different.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] Arrays are fixed-size lists whose values are of the same type.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] Rust's ownership system consists of rules that ensure memory safety without using a garbage collector.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] At compile time, each value must be attached to a variable called the *owner* of that value, and every value must have exactly one owner.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] Values are moved between different owners through assignment or passing a value as a function parameter.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] Values can also be *borrowed,* meaning they are temporarily passed to a different function before being returned to the owner.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] Because of these ownership rules, Rust types are known as *affine types*, meaning each value may be used at most once.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] This enforces a form of software fault isolation as the owner of a value is solely responsible for its correctness and deallocation.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] When a value goes out of scope, it is *dropped* by running its destructor.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] The destructor may be programmatically defined through implementing the `Drop` trait.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] This helps manage resources such as file handles, network sockets, and locks, since when objects are dropped, the resources associated with them are closed or released automatically.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] Object lifetime refers to the period of time during which a reference is valid; that is, the time between the object creation and destruction.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] These *lifetimes* are implicitly associated with all Rust reference types.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] While often inferred, they can also be indicated explicitly with named lifetime parameters (often denoted `'a`, `'b`, and so on).
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] A value's lifetime in Rust is inferred from the set of locations in the source code (i.e., function, line, and column numbers) for which a variable is valid.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] For example, a reference to a local variable has a lifetime from the expression it is declared in up until the last use of it.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] The borrow checker in the Rust compiler then enforces that references are only used in the locations of the source code where the associated lifetime is valid.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] In the example above, storing a reference to variable `x` in `r` is valid, as variable `x` has a longer lifetime (`'a`) than variable `r` (`'b`).
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] Since the lifetime of the referenced variable (`'b`) is shorter than the lifetime of the variable holding the reference (`'a`), the borrow checker errors, preventing `x` from being used from outside its scope.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] Lifetimes can be indicated using explicit *lifetime parameters* on function arguments.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] In the compiler, ownership and lifetimes work together to prevent memory safety issues such as dangling pointers.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] User-defined types are created with the `struct` or `enum` keywords.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] The `struct` keyword is used to denote a record type that groups multiple related values.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] `enum`s can take on different variants at runtime, with their capabilities similar to algebraic data types found in functional programming languages.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] Both records and enum variants can contain fields with different types.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] Alternative names, or aliases, for the same type can be defined with the `type` keyword.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] The `impl` keyword can define methods for a user-defined type.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] Data and functions are defined separately.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] Implementations fulfill a role similar to that of classes within other languages.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] The Rust standard library defines and implements many widely used custom data types, including core data structures such as `Vec`, `Option`, and `HashMap`, as well as smart pointer types.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] Rust provides a way to exclude most of the standard library using the attribute `#![no_std]`, for applications such as embedded devices.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] Internally, the standard library is divided into three parts, `core`, `alloc`, and `std`, where `std` and `alloc` are excluded by `#![no_std]`.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] Similarly, Rust's result type `Result<T, E>` holds either a successfully computed value (the `Ok` variant) or an error (the `Err` variant).
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] Like `Option`, the use of `Result` means that the inner value cannot be used directly; programmers must use a `match` expression, syntactic sugar such as `?` (the "try" operator), or an explicit `unwrap` assertion to access it.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] Both `Option` and `Result` are used throughout the standard library and are a fundamental part of Rust's explicit approach to handling errors and missing data.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] The `&` and `&mut` reference types are guaranteed to not be null and point to valid memory.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] The raw pointer types `*const` and `*mut` opt out of the safety guarantees, thus they may be null or invalid; however, it is impossible to dereference them unless the code is explicitly declared unsafe through the use of an `unsafe` block.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] Unlike dereferencing, the creation of raw pointers is allowed inside safe Rust code.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] Rust provides no implicit type conversion (coercion) between most primitive types.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] But, explicit type conversion (casting) can be performed using the `as` keyword.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] Rust supports polymorphism through traits, generic functions, and trait objects.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] The example above includes a method `is_zero` which provides a default implementation that may be overridden when implementing the trait.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] In the examples above, `Num: Zero` as well as `where Self: PartialEq` are trait bounds that constrain the type to only allow types that implement `Zero` or `PartialEq`.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] Within a trait or impl, `Self` refers to the type that the code is implementing.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] Generics can be used in functions to allow implementing a behavior for different types without repeating the same code (see bounded parametric polymorphism).
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] Generic functions can be written in relation to other generics, without knowing the actual type.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] By default, traits use static dispatch: the compiler monomorphizes the function for each concrete type instance, yielding performance equivalent to type-specific code at the cost of longer compile times and larger binaries.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] When the exact type is not known at compile time, Rust provides trait objects `&dyn Trait` and `Box<dyn Trait>`.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] Trait object calls use dynamic dispatch via a lookup table; a trait object is a "fat pointer" carrying both a data pointer and a method table pointer.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] This indirection adds a small runtime cost, but it keeps a single copy of the code and reduces binary size.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] Only "object-safe" traits are eligible to be used as trait objects.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] This approach is similar to duck typing, where all data types that implement a given trait can be treated as functionally interchangeable.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] If an element in the list does not implement the `Display` trait, it will cause a compile-time error.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] Memory and other resources are instead managed through the "resource acquisition is initialization" convention, with optional reference counting.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] Rust provides deterministic management of resources, with very low overhead.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] Values are allocated on the stack by default, and all dynamic allocations must be explicit.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] The built-in reference types using the `&` symbol do not involve run-time reference counting.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] The safety and validity of the underlying pointers are verified at compile time, preventing dangling pointers and other forms of undefined behavior.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] Rust's type system separates shared, immutable references of the form `&T` from unique, mutable references of the form `&mut T`.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] A mutable reference can be coerced to an immutable reference, but not vice versa.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] Rust's memory safety checks (See #Safety) may be circumvented through the use of `unsafe` blocks.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] This allows programmers to dereference arbitrary raw pointers, call external code, or perform other low-level functionality not allowed by safe Rust.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] Some low-level functionality enabled in this way includes volatile memory access, architecture-specific intrinsics, type punning, and inline assembly.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] Unsafe code is needed, for example, in the implementation of data structures.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] A frequently cited example is that it is difficult or impossible to implement doubly linked lists in safe Rust.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] Programmers using unsafe Rust are considered responsible for upholding Rust's memory and type safety requirements, for example, that no two mutable references exist pointing to the same location.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] If programmers write code that violates these requirements, this results in undefined behavior.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] The Rust documentation includes a list of behaviors considered undefined, including accessing dangling or misaligned pointers, or breaking the aliasing rules for references.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] Macros allow the generation and transformation of Rust code to reduce repetition.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] Macros come in two forms, with *declarative macros* defined through `macro_rules!`, and *procedural macros*, which are defined in separate crates.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] A declarative macro (also called a "macro by example") is a macro, defined using the `macro_rules!` keyword, that uses pattern matching to determine its expansion.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] In this example, the macro named `sum` is defined using the form `macro_rules! sum {` `(...) => { ... } }`.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] The first part inside the parentheses of the definition, the macro pattern `( $initial:expr $(, $expr:expr )* $(,)? )` specifies the structure of input it can take.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] Here, `$initial:expr` represents the first expression, while `$(, $expr:expr )*` means there can be zero or more additional comma-separated expressions after it.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] The trailing `$(,)?` allows the caller to optionally include a final comma without causing an error.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] The second part, after the arrow `=>`, describes what code will be generated when the macro is invoked.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] In this case, `$initial $(+ $expr)*` means that the generated code will start with the first expression, followed by a `+` and each of the additional expressions in sequence.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] The `*` again means "repeat this pattern zero or more times".
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] This means, when the macro is later called in line 8, as `sum!(1, 2, 3)`, the macro will resolve to `1 + 2 + 3` representing the addition of all of the passed expressions.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] Procedural macros are Rust functions that run and modify the compiler's input token stream, before any other components are compiled.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] They are generally more flexible than declarative macros, but are more difficult to maintain due to their complexity.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] Rust supports the creation of foreign function interfaces (FFI) through the `extern` keyword.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] A function that uses the C calling convention can be written using `extern "C" fn`.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] The `#[repr(C)]` attribute enables deterministic memory layouts for `struct`s and `enum`s for use across FFI boundaries.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] External libraries such as `bindgen` and `cxx` can generate Rust bindings for C/C++.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] Safety properties guaranteed by Rust include memory safety, type safety, and data race freedom.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] As described above, these guarantees can be circumvented by using the `unsafe` keyword.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] Memory safety includes the absence of dereferences to null, dangling, and misaligned pointers, and the absence of buffer overflows and double free errors.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] Memory leaks may occur as a result of creating reference-counted pointers that point at each other (a reference cycle) or can be deliberately created through calling `Box::leak`.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] The Rust ecosystem includes its compiler, its standard library, and additional components for software development.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] Component installation is typically managed by `rustup`, a Rust toolchain installer developed by the Rust project.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] The Rust compiler, `rustc`, compiles Rust code into binaries.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] First, the compiler parses the source code into an AST.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] The compiler backend is then invoked as a subcomponent to apply optimizations and translate the resulting IR into object code.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] Finally, a linker is used to combine the object(s) into a single executable image.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] rustc uses LLVM as its compiler backend by default, but it also supports using alternative backends such as GCC and Cranelift.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] The intention of those alternative backends is to increase platform coverage of Rust or to improve compilation times.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] Cargo is Rust's build system and package manager.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] It downloads, compiles, distributes, and uploads packages—called *crates*—that are maintained in an official registry.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] It also acts as a front-end for Clippy and other Rust components.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] By default, Cargo sources its dependencies from the user-contributed registry *crates.io*, but Git repositories, crates in the local filesystem, and other external sources can also be specified as dependencies.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] Cargo supports reproducible builds through two metadata files: Cargo.toml and Cargo.lock.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] Cargo.toml declares each package used and their version requirements.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] Cargo.lock is generated automatically during dependency resolution and records exact versions of all dependencies, including transitive dependencies.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] It formats whitespace and indentation to produce code in accordance with a common style, unless otherwise specified.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] It can be invoked as a standalone program or from a Rust project through Cargo.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] Clippy is Rust's built-in linting tool to improve the correctness, performance, and readability of Rust code.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] Following Rust 1.0, new features are developed in *nightly* versions, which are released daily.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] During each six-week release cycle, changes to nightly versions are released to beta, while changes from the previous beta version are released to a new stable version.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] Every two or three years, a new "edition" is produced.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] Editions are released to allow making limited breaking changes, such as promoting `await` to a keyword to support async/await features.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] Crates targeting different editions can interoperate with each other, so a crate can upgrade to a new edition even if its callers or its dependencies still target older editions.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] Migration to a new edition can be assisted with automated tooling.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] Since it performs no garbage collection, Rust is often faster than other memory-safe languages.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] Most of Rust's memory safety guarantees impose no runtime overhead, with the notable exception of array indexing which is checked at runtime by default.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] The performance impact of array indexing bounds checks varies, but can be significant in some cases.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] Many of Rust's features are so-called *zero-cost abstractions*, meaning they are optimized away at compile time and incur no runtime penalty.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] The ownership and borrowing system permits zero-copy implementations for some performance-sensitive tasks, such as parsing.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] Static dispatch is used by default to eliminate method calls, except for methods called on dynamic trait objects.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] The compiler uses inline expansion to eliminate function calls and statically dispatched method invocations.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] Unlike C and C++, Rust allows the compiler to reorder struct and enum elements unless a `#[repr(C)]` representation attribute is applied.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] This allows the compiler to produce more efficient code in some cases.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] Performance improvements in LLVM carry over to Rust.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] In web services, OpenDNS, a DNS resolution service owned by Cisco, uses Rust internally.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] Amazon Web Services uses Rust in "performance-sensitive components" of services.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] In 2019, AWS open-sourced Firecracker, a virtualization solution primarily written in Rust.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] Microsoft Azure IoT Edge, a platform used to run Azure services on IoT devices, has components implemented in Rust.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] Microsoft also uses Rust to run containerized modules with WebAssembly and Kubernetes.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] Cloudflare, a company providing content delivery network services, used Rust to build a new web proxy named Pingora for increased performance and efficiency.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] The npm package manager used Rust for its production authentication service in 2019.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] In operating systems, the Linux kernel began introducing experimental support for Rust code in Version 6.1 in late 2022, as part of the Rust for Linux project.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] The first drivers written in Rust were included in version 6.8.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] In 2025, kernel developers at the Linux Kernel Developers Summit determined the project to be a success, and Rust usage for kernel code will no longer be considered experimental.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] The Android developers used Rust in 2021 to rewrite existing components.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] Microsoft has rewritten parts of Windows in Rust.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] The r9 project aims to re-implement Plan 9 from Bell Labs in Rust.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] Rust has also been used in the development of new operating systems such as Redox, a "Unix-like" operating system and microkernel, Theseus, an experimental operating system with modular state management, and most of Fuchsia.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] Rust is used for command-line tools and operating system components such as stratisd, a file system manager and COSMIC, a desktop environment by System76.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] In web development, Deno, a secure runtime for JavaScript and TypeScript, is built on top of V8 using Rust and Tokio.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] Other notable adoptions in this space include Ruffle, an open-source SWF emulator, and Polkadot, an open source blockchain and cryptocurrency platform.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] Components from the Servo browser engine (funded by Mozilla and Samsung) were incorporated in the Gecko browser engine underlying Firefox.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] In January 2023, Google (Alphabet) announced support for using third party Rust libraries in Chromium.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] In other uses, Discord, an instant messaging software company, rewrote parts of its system in Rust for increased performance in 2020.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] In the same year, Dropbox announced that its file synchronization had been rewritten in Rust.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] Facebook (Meta) used Rust to redesign its system that manages source code for internal projects.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] In the 2025 Stack Overflow Developer Survey, 14.8% of respondents had recently done extensive development in Rust.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] The survey named Rust the "most admired programming language" annually from 2016 to 2025 (inclusive), as measured by the number of existing developers interested in continuing to work in the language.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] In 2025, 29.2% of developers not currently working in Rust expressed an interest in doing so.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] Rust's safety and performance have been investigated in programming languages research.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] In other fields, a journal article published to *Proceedings of the International Astronomical Union* used Rust to simulate multi-planet systems.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] An article published in *Nature* shared stories of bioinformaticians using Rust.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] Both articles cited Rust's performance and safety as advantages, and the learning curve as being a primary drawback to Rust adoption.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] The 2025 DARPA project TRACTOR aims to automatically translate C to Rust using techniques such as static analysis, dynamic analysis, and large language models.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] According to the *MIT Technology Review*, the Rust community has been seen as "unusually friendly" to newcomers and particularly attracted people from the queer community, partly due to its code of conduct.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] Inclusiveness has been cited as an important factor for some Rust developers.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] The official Rust blog collects and publishes demographic data each year.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] The **Rust Foundation** is a non-profit membership organization incorporated in United States; it manages the Rust trademark, infrastructure, and assets.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] It was established on February 8, 2021, with five founding corporate members (Amazon Web Services, Huawei, Google, Microsoft, and Mozilla).
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] The foundation's board was chaired by Shane Miller, with Ashley Williams as interim executive director.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] In late 2021, Rebecca Rumbul became executive director and CEO.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] The Rust project is maintained by 8 top-level *teams* as of November 2025: the leadership council, compiler team, dev tools team, infrastructure team, language team, launching pad, library team, and moderation team.
[src:robyn-python/rust-programming-language] The leadership council oversees the project and is formed by representatives among the other teams.
[src:robyn-python/web-framework] A **web framework** (**WF**), **web application framework** (**WAF**), or **web development framework** is a software framework that is designed to support the development of web applications including web services, web resources, and web APIs.
[src:robyn-python/web-framework] Web frameworks provide a standard way to build and deploy web applications on the World Wide Web.
[src:robyn-python/web-framework] Web frameworks aim to automate the overhead associated with common activities performed in web development.
[src:robyn-python/web-framework] For example, many web frameworks provide libraries for database access, templating frameworks, and session management, and they often promote code reuse.
[src:robyn-python/web-framework] Although they often target development of dynamic web sites, they are also applicable to static websites.
[src:robyn-python/web-framework] As the design of the World Wide Web was not inherently dynamic, early hypertext consisted of hand-coded HTML text files that were published on web servers.
[src:robyn-python/web-framework] Any modifications to published pages needed to be performed by the pages' author.
[src:robyn-python/web-framework] In 1993, the Common Gateway Interface (CGI) standard was introduced for interfacing external applications with web servers, to provide a dynamic web page that reflected user inputs.
[src:robyn-python/web-framework] Original implementations of the CGI interface typically had adverse effects on the server load however, because each request started a separate process.
[src:robyn-python/web-framework] More recent implementations utilize persistent processes amongst other techniques to reduce the footprint in the server's resources and offer a general performance boost.
[src:robyn-python/web-framework] In 1995, fully integrated server/language development environments first emerged and new web-specific languages were introduced, such as ColdFusion, PHP, and Active Server Pages.
[src:robyn-python/web-framework] Although the vast majority of languages for creating dynamic web pages have libraries to help with common tasks, web applications often require specific libraries for particular tasks, such as creating HTML (for example, Jakarta Faces).
[src:robyn-python/web-framework] In the late 1990s, mature, "full stack" frameworks began to appear, that often gathered multiple libraries useful for web development into a single cohesive software stack for web developers to use.
[src:robyn-python/web-framework] Most web frameworks are based on the model–view–controller (MVC) pattern.
[src:robyn-python/web-framework] Many frameworks follow the MVC architectural pattern to separate the data model into business rules (the "controller") and the user interface (the "view").
[src:robyn-python/web-framework] This is generally considered a good practice as it modularizes code, promotes code reuse, and allows multiple interfaces to be applied.
[src:robyn-python/web-framework] In web applications, this permits different views to be presented, for example serving different web pages for mobile vs. desktop browsers, or providing machine-readable web service interfaces.
[src:robyn-python/web-framework] Most MVC frameworks follow a push-based architecture also called "action-based".
[src:robyn-python/web-framework] These frameworks use actions that do the required processing, and then "push" the data to the view layer to render the results.
[src:robyn-python/web-framework] An alternative to this is pull-based architecture, sometimes also called "component-based".
[src:robyn-python/web-framework] These frameworks start with the view layer, which can then "pull" results from multiple controllers as needed.
[src:robyn-python/web-framework] In this architecture, multiple controllers can be involved with a single view.
[src:robyn-python/web-framework] In three-tier organization, applications are structured around three physical tiers: client, application, and database.
[src:robyn-python/web-framework] The application contains the business logic, running on a server and communicates with the client using HTTP.
[src:robyn-python/web-framework] The client on web applications is a web browser that runs HTML generated by the application layer.
[src:robyn-python/web-framework] The term should not be confused with MVC, where, unlike in three-tier architecture, it is considered a good practice to keep business logic away from the controller, the "middle layer".
[src:robyn-python/web-framework] Web frameworks must function according to the architectural rules of browsers and protocols such as HTTP, which is stateless.
[src:robyn-python/web-framework] Webpages are served up by a server and can then be modified by the browser using JavaScript.
[src:robyn-python/web-framework] Either approach has its advantages and disadvantages.
[src:robyn-python/web-framework] Server-side page changes typically require that the page be refreshed, but allow any language to be used and more computing power to be utilized.
[src:robyn-python/web-framework] Client-side changes allow the page to be updated in small chunks which feels like a desktop application, but are limited to JavaScript and run in the user's browser, which may have limited computing power.
[src:robyn-python/web-framework] Applications which make heavy use of JavaScript and only refresh parts of the page, are called single-page applications and typically make use of a client-side JavaScript web framework to organize the code.
[src:robyn-python/web-framework] Examples include Backbone.js, AngularJS, Angular, Ember.js, ReactJS, jQuery UI, Svelte, and Vue.js.
[src:robyn-python/web-framework] JavaScript-based web application frameworks, such as React and Vue, provide extensive capabilities but come with associated trade-offs.
[src:robyn-python/web-framework] These frameworks often extend or enhance features available through native web technologies, such as routing, component-based development, and state management.
[src:robyn-python/web-framework] Frameworks can introduce abstraction layers that may contribute to performance overhead, larger bundle sizes, and increased complexity.
[src:robyn-python/web-framework] Modern frameworks, such as React 18 and Vue 3, address these challenges with features like concurrent rendering, tree-shaking, and selective hydration.
[src:robyn-python/web-framework] While these advancements improve rendering efficiency and resource management, their benefits depend on the specific application and implementation context.
[src:robyn-python/web-framework] Lightweight frameworks, such as Svelte and Preact, take different architectural approaches, with Svelte eliminating the virtual DOM entirely in favor of compiling components to efficient JavaScript code, and Preact offering a minimal, compatible alternative to React.
[src:robyn-python/web-framework] Framework choice depends on an application’s requirements, including the team’s expertise, performance goals, and development priorities.
[src:robyn-python/web-framework] A newer category of web frameworks, including enhance.dev, Astro, and Fresh, leverages native web standards while minimizing abstractions and development tooling.
[src:robyn-python/web-framework] These solutions emphasize progressive enhancement, server-side rendering, and optimizing performance.
[src:robyn-python/web-framework] Astro renders static HTML by default while hydrating only interactive parts.
[src:robyn-python/web-framework] Fresh focuses on server-side rendering with zero runtime overhead.
[src:robyn-python/web-framework] Enhance.dev prioritizes progressive enhancement patterns using Web Components.
[src:robyn-python/web-framework] While these tools reduce reliance on client-side JavaScript by shifting logic to build-time or server-side execution, they still use JavaScript where necessary for interactivity.
[src:robyn-python/web-framework] This approach makes them particularly suitable for performance-critical and content-focused applications.
[src:robyn-python/web-framework] Frameworks typically set the control flow of a program and allow the user of the framework to "hook into" that flow by exposing various events.
[src:robyn-python/web-framework] This "inversion of control" design pattern is considered to be a defining principle of a framework, and benefits the code by enforcing a common flow for a team which everyone can customize in similar ways.
[src:robyn-python/web-framework] For example, some popular "microframeworks" such as Ruby's Sinatra (which inspired Express.js) allow for "middleware" hooks prior to and after HTTP requests.
[src:robyn-python/web-framework] These middleware functions can be anything, and allow the user to define logging, authentication and session management, and redirecting.
[src:robyn-python/web-framework] Web caching is the caching of web documents in order to reduce bandwidth usage, server load, and perceived "lag".
[src:robyn-python/web-framework] A web cache stores copies of documents passing through it; subsequent requests may be satisfied from the cache if certain conditions are met.
[src:robyn-python/web-framework] Some application frameworks provide mechanisms for caching documents and bypassing various stages of the page's preparation, such as database access or template interpretation.
[src:robyn-python/web-framework] Some web frameworks come with authentication and authorization frameworks, that enable the web server to identify the users of the application, and restrict access to functions based on some defined criteria.
[src:robyn-python/web-framework] Drupal is one example that provides role-based access to pages, and provides a web-based interface for creating users and assigning them roles.
[src:robyn-python/web-framework] Many web frameworks create a unified API to a database backend, enabling web applications to work with a variety of databases with no code changes, and allowing programmers to work with higher-level concepts.
[src:robyn-python/web-framework] Additionally, some object-oriented frameworks contain mapping tools to provide object-relational mapping, which maps objects to tuples.
[src:robyn-python/web-framework] Some frameworks minimize web application configuration through the use of introspection and/or following well-known conventions.
[src:robyn-python/web-framework] For example, many Java frameworks use Hibernate as a persistence layer, which can generate a database schema at runtime capable of persisting the necessary information.
[src:robyn-python/web-framework] This allows the application designer to design business objects without needing to explicitly define a database schema.
[src:robyn-python/web-framework] Frameworks such as Ruby on Rails can also work in reverse, that is, define properties of model objects at runtime based on a database schema.
[src:robyn-python/web-framework] Other features web frameworks may provide include transactional support and database migration tools.
[src:robyn-python/web-framework] A framework's URL mapping or routing facility is the mechanism by which the framework interprets URLs.
[src:robyn-python/web-framework] Some frameworks, such as Drupal and Django, match the provided URL against pre-determined patterns using regular expressions, while some others use rewriting techniques to translate the provided URL into one that the underlying engine will recognize.
[src:robyn-python/web-framework] Another technique is that of graph traversal such as used by Zope, where a URL is decomposed in steps that traverse an object graph (of models and views).
[src:robyn-python/web-framework] A URL mapping system that uses pattern matching or rewriting to route and handle requests allows for shorter more "friendly URLs" to be used, increasing the simplicity of the site and allowing for better indexing by search engines.
[src:robyn-python/web-framework] For example, a URL that ends with "/page.cgi?cat=science&topic=physics" could be changed to simply "/page/science/physics".
[src:robyn-python/web-framework] This makes the URL easier for people to remember, read and write, and provides search engines with better information about the structural layout of the site.
[src:robyn-python/web-framework] A graph traversal approach also tends to result in the creation of friendly URLs.
[src:robyn-python/web-framework] A shorter URL such as "/page/science" tends to exist by default as that is simply a shorter form of the longer traversal to "/page/science/physics".
[src:robyn-python/web-framework] Ajax, shorthand for "*Asynchronous JavaScript and XML*", is a web development technique for creating web applications.
[src:robyn-python/web-framework] The intent is to make web pages feel more responsive by exchanging small amounts of data with the server behind the scenes, so that the entire web page does not have to be reloaded each time the user requests a change.
[src:robyn-python/web-framework] This is intended to increase a web page's interactivity, speed, maintainability, and usability.
[src:robyn-python/web-framework] Due to the complexity of Ajax programming in JavaScript, there are numerous Ajax frameworks that exclusively deal with Ajax support.
[src:robyn-python/web-framework] Some Ajax frameworks are even embedded as a part of larger frameworks.
[src:robyn-python/web-framework] For example, the jQuery JavaScript library is included in Ruby on Rails.
[src:robyn-python/web-framework] With the increased interest in developing "Web 2.0" rich web applications, the complexity of programming directly in Ajax and JavaScript has become so apparent that compiler technology has stepped in, to allow developers to code in high-level languages such as Java, Python and Ruby.
[src:robyn-python/web-framework] The first of these compilers was Morfik followed by Google Web Toolkit, with ports to Python and Ruby in the form of Pyjs and RubyJS following some time after.
[src:robyn-python/web-framework] These compilers and their associated widget set libraries make the development of rich media Ajax applications much more akin to that of developing desktop applications.
[src:robyn-python/web-framework] Some frameworks provide tools for creating and providing web services.
[src:robyn-python/web-framework] These utilities may offer similar tools as the rest of the web application.
[src:robyn-python/web-framework] A number of newer Web 2.0 RESTful frameworks are now providing resource-oriented architecture (ROA) infrastructure for building collections of resources in a sort of Semantic Web ontology, based on concepts from Resource Description Framework (RDF).
